         	</div>
         </div>
		<div class="col-md-4 mb-5">
         	<div class="card h-100">
            	<div class="card-body">
                	<h2 class="card-title">Cats</h2><br>
						<h5>Brushing</h5>
                    	<p class="card-text">Brushing your cat not only removes dirt, grease and dead hair from her coat, but it helps to remove skin flakes and stimulates blood circulation, improving the overall condition of her skin. One or two brushings per week will help kitty to keep her healthy glow—and you’ll find that regular sessions are especially beneficial when your cat ages and is no longer able to groom so meticulously on her own.hed, though some definitely shed more than others. Regular brushing will help keep shedding under control.</p>
						<h5>Bathing</h5>
						<p>With her built-in grooming tools (tongue and teeth), your fastidious feline is well-equipped to tackle her own hair care needs. But if she is very dirty or gets into something sticky or smelly, you may need to give her a bath. Make sure her claws are trimmed before bathing for your own safety, gently place some cotton in the ears to keep water out, and be sure to thoroughly dry after the bath is complete.</p>
						<h5>Trimming</h5>
						<p>Create a quiet, peaceful environment for her to relax, it's important that the cat feel soothed before attempting to cut her nails. You can further improve this by making sounds with the clippers before trimming aswell. Do not forget to regularly and gently massage your cat's paws, as to help her get used to you handling her feet. Be sure to only trim the <strong>white</strong> parts of the nail, as the <strong>pink</strong> areas contain the majority of the nerve endings, and are incredibly sensitive to the touch; aswell as being prone to bleeding. </p>
             	</div>
